Fraud
The act defines fraud as dishonestly obtaining property or causing loss or risk of loss 
to another person by any false pretense or by means of any other fraudulent conduct, 
The punishment for fraud in Ghana depends on the severity of the offense.For instance, 
a person found guilty of fraud involving an amount not exceeding GH¢100 is liable to 
imprisonment for a term not exceeding six months or a fine not exceeding GH¢600 or both.On the other hand, a person found guilty of fraud involving an amount exceeding GH¢10,000 is liable to imprisonment for a term not less than five years and not more than 25 years.

Attempt to commit a criminal offence
Under the Criminal Offences Act, 1960 (Act 29) of Ghana, an attempt to commit a criminal offense is also considered a criminal offense.Section 18 of the Act defines an attempt as when a person begins to do an act which is a step towards the commission of an offense, with the intention to
commit that offense, but does not complete it.The punishment for attempted criminal offenses in Ghana depends on the severity of the offense that the person intended to commit.For instance, if the offense intended was a misdemeanor, the person found guilty of an attempt can be sentenced to imprisonment for a term not exceeding one year, or to a fine or both. If the offense intended was a felony, the punishment for an attempt may be the same as if the offense was actually committed.

Abetment of a criminal offence
In Ghana the Abetment of a Criminal Offence is covered under the Criminal Offences Act, 1960 (Act 29) and the Criminal Procedure Code, 1960 (Act 30). Abetment of a criminal offence is a serious offence and is punishable under the law.According to the Criminal Offences Act, abetment is defined as aiding, counseling, procuring or commanding another person to commit an offence. It is a criminal offence to abet someone to commit a crime, even if the abettor did not actually participate in the commission of the crime.


Assault and battery
Under Ghanaian law, assault is categorized into two types: simple assault and aggravated assault.Simple assault involves an intentional act that causes harm or the apprehension of harm to another person, while aggravated assault involves an assault with a weapon or an assault that causes severe bodily harm.The punishment for assault in Ghana varies depending on the severity of the offense.For simple assault, the offender can face up to three years in prison, a fine, or both.For aggravated assault, the offender can face up to ten years in prison, a fine, or both.


Kidnapping
Kidnapping is a serious criminal offense under Ghanaian law, and it is punishable by imprisonment for a term of not less than five years and not more than twenty-five years.The Criminal Offences Act, 1960 (Act 29) provides for the offense of kidnapping.Section 92 of the Act defines kidnapping as the unlawful confinement or detention of a person against their will, with the intent to cause them to be unlawfully transported, concealed, or held for ransom, reward, or other purposes.


Abduction
Abduction is a criminal offense in Ghana, and it is punishable under the Criminal Offences Act, 1960 (Act 29).The act defines abduction as the unlawful taking or detention of a person against their will, either by force or by deceit, for the purpose of demanding a ransom or for any other unlawful purpose.Under Ghanaian law, abduction is considered a serious offense, and anyone found guilty of abduction may face imprisonment or fines or both.The punishment for abduction depends on the circumstances of the case, including the age of the victim and the motive behind the abduction.

Rape
In Ghana, rape is a serious criminal offense, and it is punishable under the Criminal Offenses Act, 1960 (Act 29).The act defines rape as sexual intercourse with a person without their consent.Under Ghanaian law, consent must be given freely and voluntarily by a person who is capable of giving consent.If a person is under the influence of drugs or alcohol, mentally incapacitated, or unable to give consent for any other reason, any sexual activity with that person is considered rape.The punishment for rape in Ghana varies depending on the circumstances of the case.If the victim is under the age of 16 or is mentally challenged, the offender may face life imprisonment.If the victim is over the age of 16, the offender may face a term of imprisonment of not less than five years and not more than 25 years.


Murder
Murder is a serious criminal offense in Ghana, and it is punishable under the Criminal Offences Act, 1960 (Act 29).The act defines murder as the intentional killing of a person, either with premeditation or with malice aforethought.Under Ghanaian law, murder is punishable by death or life imprisonment.However, in practice, Ghana has a de facto moratorium on the use of the death penalty, and the sentence of life imprisonment is the most severe penalty that is usually imposed for murder.There are certain circumstances under which a murder charge can be reduced to manslaughter, such as when the killing was done in the heat of passion, in self-defense, or by accident.Manslaughter is also a criminal offense in Ghana, and it is punishable by imprisonment for a term of not less than five years and not more than 25 years.


Attempt to commit murder
Under Ghanaian law, attempt to commit murder is a serious criminal offense.The offense is defined under Section 18 of the Criminal Offences Act, 1960 (Act 29) as amended by the Criminal Offences (Amendment) Act, 2003 (Act 646).The law states that any person who attempts to commit murder commits a felony and is liable, upon conviction, to imprisonment for a term of not less than ten years and not more than twenty-five years.To be found guilty of attempt to commit murder, the prosecution must prove beyond a reasonable doubt that the defendant had the specific intent to commit murder and took some substantial step towards carrying out the act, but for some reason, the attempt was not successful.


Manslaughter
Under Ghanaian law, manslaughter is a criminal offense that is less severe than murder, but still punishable by significant penalties.The offense is defined under Section 52 of the Criminal Offences Act, 1960 (Act 29) as amended by the Criminal Offences (Amendment) Act, 2003 (Act 646).The law states that any person who unlawfully kills another person without malice aforethought commits manslaughter and is liable, upon conviction, to imprisonment for a term of not less than five years and not more than twenty-five years.In Ghana, there are two types of manslaughter: voluntary and involuntary manslaughter.Voluntary manslaughter occurs when the accused person intentionally kills another person in the heat of passion, while involuntary manslaughter occurs when the accused person kills another person unintentionally, but as a result of recklessness or negligence.The prosecution must prove beyond a reasonable doubt that the accused person caused the death of another person unlawfully.The defense may argue that the death was accidental, or that the accused acted in self-defense or in defense of others.


Provocation
Under Ghanaian law, the defense of provocation can be used in certain criminal cases to reduce a charge of murder to one of voluntary manslaughter.The defense is recognized under Section 50 of the Criminal Offences Act, 1960 (Act 29) as amended by the Criminal Offences (Amendment) Act, 2003 (Act 646).The defense of provocation can be raised when the accused person's actions were the result of a sudden and temporary loss of self-control caused by a serious and sudden provocation.The provocation must be of such a nature that it would cause a reasonable person to lose their self-control, and the accused must have acted in the heat of passion before there was time for their passion to cool.If the defense of provocation is successfully raised, the charge of murder may be reduced to one of voluntary manslaughter, which carries a less severe penalty.It is important to note, however, that the defense of provocation is not available in cases where the accused person deliberately sought to provoke the victim, or where the provocation was the result of a lawful act.The defense is also not available in cases where the accused person had a premeditated plan to commit the crime.



Abetment or enabling of suicide
Under Ghanaian law, the defense of provocation can be used in certain criminal cases to reduce a charge of murder to one of voluntary manslaughter.The defense is recognized under Section 50 of the Criminal Offences Act, 1960 (Act 29) as amended by the Criminal Offences (Amendment) Act, 2003 (Act 646).The defense of provocation can be raised when the accused person's actions were the result of a sudden and temporary loss of self-control caused by a serious and sudden provocation.The provocation must be of such a nature that it would cause a reasonable person to lose their self-control, and the accused must have acted in the heat of passion before there was time for their passion to cool.If the defense of provocation is successfully raised, the charge of murder may be reduced to one of voluntary manslaughter, which carries a less severe penalty.


Abortion or miscarriage
In Ghana, abortion is a criminal offense, except in certain limited circumstances.The law on abortion is contained in the Criminal Code, 1960 (Act 29) as amended by the Criminal Code (Amendment) Act, 2003 (Act 646).Section 58 of the Criminal Code states that any person who with intent to procure miscarriage of a woman, whether the woman is pregnant or not, unlawfully administers to her any poison or other noxious thing, or unlawfully uses any instrument or other means whatsoever, commits a felony and is liable, upon conviction, to imprisonment for a term of not less than three years and not more than ten years.However, the law allows for abortion in cases where the pregnancy poses a risk to the life or health of the woman or where the pregnancy is the result of rape, incest, or defilement.In such cases, a qualified medical practitioner may perform the abortion with the consent of the woman or her legal representative.In summary, abortion is a criminal offense in Ghana, except in cases where the pregnancy poses a risk to the life or health of the woman or where the pregnancy is the result of rape, incest, or defilement.Those who unlawfully administer any poison or other noxious thing to a woman or use any instrument or other means to procure miscarriage may face significant penalties, including imprisonment.


Robbery
Robbery is a criminal offense under Ghanaian law, and it is defined in Section 150 of the Criminal Offences Act, 1960 (Act 29) as amended by the Criminal Offences (Amendment) Act, 2003 (Act 646).According to the law, a person commits robbery if they use force or threaten to use force against another person in order to take their property from them.The use of force or threat of force must be used at the time of the theft or immediately before or after it.Robbery is a serious offense in Ghana, and those convicted of this offense may face significant penalties, including imprisonment for a term of not less than ten years and not more than twenty-five years.If the robbery was committed with a firearm, the penalty may be imprisonment for a term of not less than fifteen years and not more than thirty years, or even life imprisonment.


Extortion
Under Ghanaian law, extortion is a criminal offense and is defined under Section 151 of the Criminal Offences Act, 1960 (Act 29) as amended by the Criminal Offences (Amendment) Act, 2003 (Act 646).The law defines extortion as the act of obtaining property or money from someone by using force, intimidation, or the threat of harm.This can include physical violence, verbal threats, or other forms of coercion.Anyone found guilty of extortion may be punished with imprisonment for a term of not less than three years and not more than ten years.Additionally, if the offense involved the use of a firearm or other dangerous weapon, the penalty may be imprisonment for a term of not less than ten years and not more than twenty-five years.



Forgery
Forgery is a criminal offense under Ghanaian law, and it is defined in Section 159 of the Criminal Offences Act, 1960 (Act 29) as amended by the Criminal Offences (Amendment) Act, 2003 (Act 646).The law defines forgery as the act of making a false document or altering a genuine document with the intent to deceive or defraud someone.This can include forging signatures, altering dates or amounts, or creating fake documents such as certificates, licenses, or contracts.Anyone found guilty of forgery may be punished with imprisonment for a term of not less than three years and not more than ten years.Additionally, if the forgery was committed with the intent to deceive or defraud a financial institution or government entity, the penalty may be imprisonment for a term of not less than five years and not more than twenty-five years.It is worth noting that under Ghanaian law, using a forged document is also a criminal offense, and those found guilty may face penalties similar to those for the offense of forgery.


Public drunkness
Under Ghanaian law, public drunkenness is a minor offense and is regulated by the Summary Jurisdiction (Procedure) Act, 1960 (Act 220).According to the law, a person who is found drunk and incapable of taking care of themselves in a public place may be arrested and detained by the police until they have sobered up.Additionally, a person who is found drunk and causing a disturbance in a public place may also be arrested and charged with a more serious offense, such as disorderly conduct.If a person is convicted of public drunkenness, they may be fined an amount determined by the court or imprisoned for a term of not more than twenty-four hours.However, it is worth noting that the enforcement of this law is not always consistent, and in some cases, the police may choose to simply escort the intoxicated person to a safe place rather than arrest them.In summary, public drunkenness is a minor offense under Ghanaian law, and those found guilty may face penalties such as fines or short-term imprisonment.The police may also detain intoxicated persons until they have sobered up to ensure their safety.


Drunk Driving
In Ghana, it is illegal to drive under the influence of alcohol or drugs.The Road Traffic Act, 2004 (Act 683) and the Road Traffic Regulations, 2012 (LI 2180) specify the legal blood alcohol concentration (BAC) limit for drivers in Ghana as 0.08% or 80 milligrams of alcohol per 100 milliliters of blood.Under these laws, drivers who exceed the legal BAC limit can face severe penalties, including fines, imprisonment, and suspension or revocation of their driver's license.Specifically, if a driver is caught driving under the influence of alcohol, they can be fined up to GHC 5,000 (approximately USD 860), imprisoned for up to three years, or both.Additionally, the driver's license can be suspended or revoked for a period of time.If a drunk driver causes an accident resulting in injury or death, they can be charged with a more serious offense of "causing harm by reckless or dangerous driving" or "dangerous driving causing death" under the Criminal Offenses Act, 1960 (Act 29), which carries even more severe penalties, including a longer prison sentence.



Sexual Assault
Sexual assault is a serious crime in Ghana, and it is punishable under the Criminal Offences Act, 1960 (Act 29) and the Domestic Violence Act, 2007 (Act 732).Under Ghanaian law, sexual assault is defined as any non-consensual sexual act, which includes rape, indecent assault, sexual harassment, and defilement.The punishment for sexual assault varies depending on the severity of the offense.For instance, if someone is found guilty of rape, they can be sentenced to imprisonment for a term of not less than five years and not more than 25 years, depending on the circumstances of the case.Similarly, if someone is found guilty of defilement, which involves sexual intercourse with a person under the age of 16 years, they can be sentenced to imprisonment for a term of not less than seven years and not more than 25 years.


Assault without battery or violence
Under Ghanaian law, assault without actual battery is a criminal offense.Assault without battery occurs when one person intentionally causes another person to believe that they are about to be attacked or physically harmed.Section 84 of the Criminal Offences Act, 1960 (Act 29) defines assault as "the threat or use of force upon the person of another, whether or not the offender has the present ability to effect his purpose."If a person is found guilty of assault without battery, they may be punished with a fine, imprisonment for a term not exceeding three years, or both.The severity of the punishment will depend on the circumstances surrounding the assault, including the degree of fear or harm caused to the victim, as well as any aggravating factors such as the use of a weapon or the offender's previous criminal history.




Negligence
The law on negligence in Ghana is primarily governed by the common law and the Ghanaian legal system.Negligence is defined as the failure to exercise reasonable care under the circumstances, resulting in harm to another person or their property.Under Ghanaian law, a person may be found liable for negligence if they owe a duty of care to another person, they breach that duty, and the breach causes harm to the other person.The duty of care may arise in a variety of contexts, such as in the provision of medical care, the operation of a motor vehicle, or the maintenance of property.To establish a claim for negligence, the plaintiff must prove that the defendant owed them a duty of care, that the defendant breached that duty by failing to exercise reasonable care, and that the breach caused the plaintiff's injury or loss. If the plaintiff is able to establish these elements, they may be entitled to damages to compensate them for their losses.



Conspiracy
In Ghana, conspiracy is a criminal offense that is defined under the Criminal Code, 1960 (Act 29).Section 23 of the Criminal Code defines conspiracy as an agreement between two or more persons to commit a crime, or to achieve an unlawful purpose.Under Ghanaian law, a person who conspires with others to commit a crime can be charged and punished as if they had actually committed the crime.The punishment for conspiracy varies depending on the severity of the crime that was planned.For example, if the conspiracy is to commit a misdemeanor, the punishment can include imprisonment for up to three years or a fine, or both.If the conspiracy is to commit a felony, the punishment can include imprisonment for a term of between five and twenty-five years.


Harbouring or hiding a criminal
In Ghana, harbouring a criminal is a criminal offense that is defined under the Criminal Code, 1960 (Act 29).Section 18 of the Criminal Code provides that a person who knowingly harbours a criminal, or conceals a criminal from the authorities, can be charged with the offence of harbouring a criminal.The offence of harbouring a criminal is considered a serious offence in Ghana and carries severe penalties upon conviction.The punishment for harbouring a criminal can range from imprisonment for a term of up to five years, to a fine, or both.It's important to note that the prosecution of harbouring a criminal charges in Ghana requires evidence that the accused knew or had reason to believe that the person they were harbouring was a criminal.The prosecution also needs to show that the accused intentionally and knowingly concealed the criminal from the authorities or helped them avoid arrest or prosecution.
